<ab>
    <lb n="1"/>τὸ προσκύνημα Φαβρικίου παρὰ τῷ Πανὶ

    <lb n="2"/>καὶ τοῖς συνναίοις θεοῖς,

    <lb n="3" xml:id="lb3"/><app type="editorial"><lem resp="J.L. Fournet, BIFAO 95 (1995) 203"><gap reason="ellipsis" quantity="2" unit="line"><desc>Demotic</desc></gap></lem><rdg><unclear>Τ</unclear>ιβ<supplied reason="lost">ε</supplied>ρ<supplied reason="lost">ί</supplied><unclear>ο</unclear>υ <expan><ex>ἔτους</ex></expan> <num value="2">β</num>.

    <lb n="4"/>ΤΙ<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></rdg></app> 
</ab></div>
         <div type="commentary" subtype="linebyline">
            <list>
               <item corresp="#lb3" xml:space="preserve"><ref>3</ref> <p>La l. 3 loin d’être du grec, est en fait du démotique (Fournet BIFAO 95, 1995, 203).  On planche 35 (not 40 as stated in the introduction to this inscription) one can find an admirably clear squeeze of this inscription and see that lines 3 and 4 of I Ko.Ko.40 are not Greek but Demotic (Sijpestein ZPE 93, 1992, 151). I doubt that Demotic and Greek really go together as one text, Clarysse (cf. note on TM)</p></item>
            </list>
